steps.description:
Even a small bathroom can be a peaceful, relaxing getaway in your home if it gets good natural light. If possible, don't cover up your windows with dark curtains or blinds. Install curtains or blinds in a light color like oatmeal or cream; make sure they're thick enough to provide a secure screen, but thin enough to let some light in. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8f/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8f/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You could also install curtains that cover only the bottom half of your windows, letting light in through the top half. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/41/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/41/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If your bathroom is situated away from other people's view, go ahead and open the curtains or blinds to let the light shine in. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6d/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6d/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have an old-fashioned, dull yellow ceiling light - which many bathrooms do - a simple way to transform your bathroom is to update the light fixture with something more modern. Choose a light covering that helps bath the bathroom in white light, rather than yellow, which causes rooms to look gloomy and small. A small chandelier is a good choice for a tiny bathroom; it adds elegance without taking up too much space. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f4/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f4/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Track lighting can also help give the appearance of a bigger space. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4e/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4e/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Painting a room with highly contrasting color can make it look smaller, so choose paint that isn't too wildly different from your bathroom tiles. For example, if you have cream tile, painting the walls dark blue might make the space feel claustrophobic; go for a lighter shade of cream, peach, pale blue, or another color that isn't too loud. If you prefer bolder colors, consider painting the walls a neutral color and adding a more colorful trim or border. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/18/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/18/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

You could also paint just one wall a bold color and leave three walls neutral, or use wallpaper in one area and neutral paint everywhere else. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f0/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f0/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have a cabinet under your sink, there's no need to have an extra dresser in another corner of the bathroom. Clear away decorative tables, laundry hampers (they can go in your bedroom instead) and any other piece of furniture that sits on the floor of your bathroom. You'll be amazed at what a difference clearing away even a small piece of furniture can make. If you absolutely must keep a dresser or small piece of furniture in your bathroom, try to maximize space by creating a second level of usage. For example, a small dresser can double as a vanity if you hang a mirror on the wall above it. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cd/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cd/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you have a large clothes hamper that you prefer to keep in the bathroom, consider getting a cloth laundry bag instead. These take up much less space than large basket hampers. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/45/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/45/Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Decorate-a-Small-Bathroom-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
